INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '28e822a0-fe21-4d5e-b301-8150919cf9ff',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$REST + OpenAPI — Spec-First vs Code-First, and Generating Typed Clients$escape$,
  $escape$Spec-first means authoring `openapi.yaml` before any server code — your REST contract drives everything. `openapi-generator` produces server stubs and typed clients from it; frontend and backend teams work in parallel against a stable interface. Code-first flips the flow: annotate your REST routes (Swashbuckle in .NET, FastAPI's decorator system in Python) and derive the spec at runtime from your implementation.

Spec-first wins on contract clarity and team coordination; code-first wins on velocity. The real payoff in either approach is client generation. `openapi-typescript` turns an OpenAPI 3.1 spec into a fully typed `paths` interface — every REST endpoint's path params, query params, request body, and response shape are statically typed. Pair it with `openapi-fetch` and you get type-safe fetch calls with zero hand-written wrappers or manual `Response.json()` casting.

Documentation is essentially free: Swagger UI and Redoc render interactive explorers directly from your spec, including auth schemes and example payloads. With spec-first, treat `openapi.yaml` like production code — versioned in git, reviewed in PRs, never hand-edited after a generation run.$escape$,
  $escape$// 1. Generate types from your OpenAPI spec:
// npx openapi-typescript openapi.yaml -o src/api/schema.d.ts

import createClient from "openapi-fetch";
import type { paths } from "./api/schema";

const api = createClient<paths>({ baseUrl: "https://api.example.com" });

// Path params, query params, body, and response — all inferred from the spec
const { data, error } = await api.GET("/articles/{id}", {
  params: {
    path: { id: "abc-123" },
    query: { include: "author" },
  },
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
