INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9f09eb8e-10b0-449d-92d0-7bb5b932882a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$REST API Versioning — URL Path vs. Header Strategy and Backward Compatibility$escape$,
  $escape$REST APIs expose two dominant versioning strategies. URL path versioning (/v1/users, /v2/users) is explicit, cacheable, and easy to route at the gateway level — but pollutes your URI namespace and violates the REST constraint that URIs should identify resources, not versions. Header versioning (Accept: application/vnd.myapi.v2+json or a custom X-API-Version header) keeps URIs stable and aligns with HTTP content negotiation semantics, but breaks browser-based testing and complicates caching with Vary headers.

For backward compatibility, additive changes (new fields, new optional query params) are safe without bumping versions. Breaking changes — removing fields, changing data types, altering response shapes — require a new version. Use a sunset header (Sunset: Sat, 01 Jan 2027 00:00:00 GMT) on deprecated endpoints to give clients a migration window. Never silently remove a version; return 410 Gone after the sunset date. In practice, most REST APIs ship URL versioning for its operational simplicity: reverse proxies, API gateways, and SDK generators all handle /v1 vs /v2 routing with zero custom middleware.$escape$,
  $escape$# URL versioning — explicit, gateway-friendly
GET /v1/users/42          # stable legacy contract
GET /v2/users/42          # new shape (e.g. name split into first_name/last_name)

# Header versioning — stable URIs, content-negotiated
GET /users/42
Accept: application/vnd.myapi.v2+json

# Sunset signal on a deprecated v1 endpoint
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Sunset: Sat, 01 Jan 2027 00:00:00 GMT
Deprecation: true
Link: <https://api.example.com/v2/users/42>; rel="successor-version"$escape$,
