INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '071fcc79-d38c-4865-b7ec-1599aac6a71d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$REST Contract Testing with Pact — Catch API Breaks Before They Hit Prod$escape$,
  $escape$REST APIs break silently — a provider renames a field, the consumer keeps expecting the old shape, and nothing catches it until production. Pact solves this with consumer-driven contract testing: the consumer defines exactly which request/response pairs it relies on, publishes a pact file, and the provider verifies it independently.

On the consumer side, Pact spins up a local mock server. You define interactions describing the HTTP method, path, and the specific fields your code actually uses — not the full response shape. This generates a pact JSON file encoding the contract.

On the provider side, `pact.verifyProvider()` replays each interaction against real handler code and checks responses match. No shared staging environment needed — each side tests independently.

For integration tests, keep scope narrow: one endpoint per test, real HTTP client (`supertest` in Node, `httpx` in Python), seeded database. Assert on status codes, `Content-Type` headers, and response shape via JSON Schema or Zod. Mock only at the HTTP boundary using MSW or WireMock — never mock your own service internals, which hides the contract drift you're trying to catch.$escape$,
  $escape$import { Pact, like } from "@pact-foundation/pact";
import { getUserById } from "./api-client";

const provider = new Pact({ consumer: "WebApp", provider: "UserService", port: 1234 });

beforeAll(() => provider.setup());
afterAll(() => provider.finalize());

it("GET /users/:id returns user shape consumer needs", async () => {
  await provider.addInteraction({
    state: "user 42 exists",
    uponReceiving: "a GET request for user 42",
    withRequest: { method: "GET", path: "/users/42", headers: { Accept: "application/json" } },
    willRespondWith: { status: 200, body: { id: 42, name: like("Alice") } },
  });
  const user = await getUserById(42); // points to http://localhost:1234
  expect(user.name).toBeDefined();
});$escape$,
