INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '958b68a9-3f5d-4f3a-af0d-dda7566e044f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$REST — Choosing Between REST, GraphQL, and gRPC: A Decision Framework$escape$,
  $escape$REST shines when HTTP semantics do real work: cache-control headers, ETags, and CDN edge caching are free wins you lose with GraphQL's POST-only model or gRPC's binary framing. Stick with REST when you're building public APIs where broad client compatibility matters, or when your resources map cleanly to nouns with standard CRUD verbs.

Switch to GraphQL when multiple clients (mobile, web, third-party) need different shapes of the same data — overfetching a user object 50 fields wide on a mobile client is a REST-native pain point GraphQL solves directly.

Reach for gRPC when you control both ends of the wire: internal service-to-service calls where Protobuf's binary encoding and HTTP/2 multiplexing reduce latency meaningfully, or when you need bidirectional streaming that REST's request-response model can't express.

The tell: if you're adding `?fields=id,name` query params to trim response size, you've outgrown REST for that endpoint. If you're hand-rolling retry logic over HTTP/1.1 between services, gRPC's built-in interceptors and status codes are worth the schema overhead.$escape$,
  $escape$// REST: leverage HTTP caching — lost in GraphQL's POST-only model
GET /api/users/42
Cache-Control: max-age=300
ETag: "abc123"

// Client conditional request — zero-byte response on cache hit
GET /api/users/42
If-None-Match: "abc123"
// → 304 Not Modified

// REST resource over-fetch signal: adding field filters = GraphQL time
GET /api/users/42?fields=id,name,avatar
// If you're doing this often, migrate that endpoint to GraphQL$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
